==== Generalizations ====
Generalizations of this definition are possible, for instance, to complex manifolds and algebraic varieties. However, instead of examining derivations formula_72 from the full algebra of functions, one must instead work at the level of germs of functions. The reason for this is that the structure sheaf may not be fine for such structures. For example, let formula_73 be an algebraic variety with structure sheaf formula_74. Then the Zariski tangent space at a point formula_75 is the collection of all formula_76-derivations formula_77, where formula_76 is the ground field and formula_79 is the stalk of formula_74 at formula_8.

=== Equivalence of the definitions ===
For formula_82 and a differentiable curve formula_83 such that formula_84 define formula_85 (where the derivative is taken in the ordinary sense because formula_86 is a function from formula_87 to formula_88). One can ascertain that formula_89 is a derivation at the point formula_90 and that equivalent curves yield the same derivation. Thus, for an equivalence class formula_91 we can define formula_92 where the curve formula_48 has been chosen arbitrarily. The map formula_94 is a vector space isomorphism between the space of the equivalence classes formula_38 and that of the derivations at the point formula_96

=== Definition via cotangent spaces === 

Again, we start with a formula_97 manifold formula_16 and a point formula_19. Consider the ideal formula_100 of formula_101 that consists of all smooth functions formula_102 vanishing at formula_1, i.e., formula_104. Then formula_100 and formula_106 are both real vector spaces, and the quotient space formula_107 can be shown to be isomorphic to the cotangent space formula_108 through the use of Taylor&#x27;s theorem. The tangent space formula_109 may then be defined as the dual space of formula_107.

While this definition is the most abstract, it is also the one that is most easily transferable to other settings, for instance, to the varieties considered in algebraic geometry.

If formula_72 is a derivation at formula_1, then formula_113 for every formula_114, which means that formula_72 gives rise to a linear map formula_116. Conversely, if formula_117 is a linear map, then formula_118 defines a derivation at formula_1. This yields an equivalence between tangent spaces defined via derivations and tangent spaces defined via cotangent spaces.

== Properties ==

If formula_16 is an open subset of formula_50, then formula_16 is a formula_56 manifold in a natural manner (take coordinate charts to be identity maps on open subsets of formula_50), and the tangent spaces are all naturally identified with formula_50.

=== Tangent vectors as directional derivatives ===

Another way to think about tangent vectors is as directional derivatives. Given a vector formula_126 in formula_50, one defines the corresponding directional derivative at a point formula_128 by
