<doc id="30844" wikidata="Q1163016" url="?curid=30844" title="Tensor product">
<text>In mathematics, the tensor product formula_1 of two vector spaces and (over the same field) is a vector space to which is associated a bilinear map formula_2 that maps a pair formula_3 to an element of formula_1 denoted .

An element of the form formula_5 is called the tensor product of and . An element of formula_1 is a tensor, and the tensor product of two vectors is sometimes called an &quot;elementary tensor&quot; or a &quot;decomposable tensor&quot;. The elementary tensors span formula_1 in the sense that every element of formula_1 is a sum of elementary tensors. If bases are given for and , a basis of formula_1 is formed by all tensor products of a basis element of and a basis element of .

The tensor product of two vector spaces captures the properties of all bilinear maps in the sense that a bilinear map from formula_10 into another vector space factors uniquely through a linear map formula_11 (see the section below titled &#x27;Universal property&#x27;), i.e. the bilinear map is associated to a unique linear map from the tensor product formula_1 to .

Tensor products are used in many application areas, including physics and engineering. For example, in general relativity, the gravitational field is described through the metric tensor, which is a tensor field with one tensor at each point of the space-time manifold, and each belonging to the tensor product of the cotangent space at the point with itself.

== Definitions and constructions ==

The &quot;tensor product&quot; of two vector spaces is a vector space that is defined up to an isomorphism. There are several equivalent ways to define it. Most consist of defining explicitly a vector space that is called a tensor product, and, generally, the equivalence proof results almost immediately from the basic properties of the vector spaces that are so defined. 

The tensor product can also be defined through a universal property; see , below. As for every universal property, all objects that satisfy the property are isomorphic through a unique isomorphism that is compatible with the universal property. When this definition is used, the other definitions may be viewed as constructions of objects satisfying the universal property and as proofs that there are objects satisfying the universal property, that is that tensor products exist.

=== From bases ===
Let and be two vector spaces over a field , with respective bases formula_13 and .

The &quot;tensor product&quot; formula_1 of and is a vector space that has as a basis the set of all formula_15 with formula_16 and . This definition can be formalized in the following way (this formalization is rarely used in practice, as the preceding informal definition is generally sufficient): formula_1 is the set of the functions from the Cartesian product formula_18 to that have a finite number of nonzero values. The pointwise operations make formula_1 a vector space. The function that maps formula_20 to and the other elements of formula_18 to is denoted .

The set formula_22 is then straightforwardly a basis of , which is called the &quot;tensor product&quot; of the bases formula_13 and .

We can equivalently define formula_1 to be the set of bilinear forms on formula_25 that are nonzero at only a finite number of elements of . To see this, given formula_26 and a bilinear form , we can decompose formula_27 and formula_28 in the bases formula_13 and formula_30 as:
formula_31
where only a finite number of formula_32&#x27;s and formula_33&#x27;s are nonzero, and find by the bilinearity of formula_34 that:
